# Accessibility Standards

## Semantic HTML

Always prefer semantic HTML elements over generic `<div>`/`<span>`:

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<div onClick={handleSave}>שמור</div>
<div role="banner"><span>כותרת</span></div>

// ✅ GOOD
<button type="button" onClick={handleSave}>שמור</button>
<header><h1>כותרת</h1></header>
```

Use `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<footer>`, `<article>` at page/layout level.

## Icon Buttons — aria-label Required

Every interactive element without visible text MUST have an `aria-label`:

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<button onClick={onClose}><XIcon /></button>

// ✅ GOOD
<button type="button" onClick={onClose} aria-label="סגור"><XIcon aria-hidden="true" /></button>
```

Mark decorative icons with `aria-hidden="true"`.

## Images & Avatars

All `<img>` elements must have an `alt` attribute:

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<img src={avatarUrl} />

// ✅ GOOD
<img src={avatarUrl} alt={`תמונת פרופיל של ${patientName}`} />
// Decorative:
<img src={decorativeBg} alt="" />
```

## Form Labels

Every `<input>`, `<select>`, and `<textarea>` must be associated with a `<label>` via `htmlFor`/`id`, or have `aria-label`.

## Focus Visibility

Never remove focus outlines without a visible replacement (`focus-visible:ring-*`).
